INSERT INTO texts VALUES(114,'Haṭha Yoga Pradīpikā (Light on Haṭha Yoga)','Yoga Texts','',NULL,'Composed in Sanskrit, the text is generally dated to the **15th century CE** (c. 1350–1500 CE). This places it in the medieval period of Indian history, a time when the practice of Hatha Yoga was being systematically codified.','Yogi Svātmārāma (or Swatmarama), a disciple of Gorakshanath, belonging to the **Natha tradition** (or Nath Sampradaya). The text is dedicated to the guru Matsyendranath and Adinath (Shiva).',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/yoga_texts_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(115,'Yoga Vasistha (योगवासिष्ठम्)','Yoga Texts','',NULL,'The text evolved over several centuries, with the earliest version (Mokṣopāya) dated to the 10th century CE in Kashmir, and the final, complete text reaching its current form between the 10th and 14th centuries CE.','Traditionally attributed to Maharishi Valmiki, but the actual author is unknown. It is a key text in the Advaita Vedanta tradition, also incorporating influences from Kashmiri Shaivism.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/yoga_texts_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(116,'Gheranda Samhita (Gheraṇḍa-saṃhitā)','Yoga Texts','',NULL,'Late **17th century CE** (circa 1700 CE). It is a relatively late text in the Hatha Yoga tradition, likely composed in the Bengal region of India.','Sage Gheranda (preceptor) and Chanda Kapali (pupil). The text belongs to the tradition of Hatha Yoga, specifically *Ghaṭastha Yoga* (vessel yoga), which focuses on purifying and strengthening the physical body as a vessel for the soul.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/yoga_texts_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(117,'Goraksha Shataka (Gorakṣaśataka)','Yoga Texts','',NULL,'Generally dated to the 11th-12th century CE, making it one of the earliest known texts on Hatha Yoga.','Attributed to the sage Gorakshanath (Gorakṣa), a foundational figure of the Nath tradition (Nath Sampradaya).',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/yoga_texts_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(118,'Adi Shankaracharya commentaries - Advaita Vedanta non-dualism','Commentaries','',NULL,'The most widely accepted scholarly dating places Adi Shankaracharya in the **8th century CE**, specifically c. 788–820 CE or c. 700–750 CE. This dating is based on historical and textual evidence, though traditional accounts from the monastic lineages (Maṭhas) often place him much earlier (e.g., 5th century BCE). The 8th-century date is generally preferred by modern scholarship.','Adi Shankaracharya (Śaṅkarācārya), the preeminent philosopher of the Advaita Vedanta (non-dualism) tradition. He is revered as a systematizer, not a founder, of the Advaita school, which traces its lineage through his teacher Govinda and Govinda''s teacher Gauḍapāda. The tradition is part of the larger Hindu philosophical system of Vedanta.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(119,'Ramanuja''s Commentaries (primarily Sri Bhashya and Gita Bhashya) on Vishishtadvaita','Commentaries','',NULL,'Born c. 1017 CE in Sriperumbudur, India; Died 1137 CE in Srirangam. His major works were composed in the 11th and 12th centuries CE.','Ramanuja (Śrī Rāmānujācārya); Tradition: Vishishtadvaita Vedanta (a school of Vaishnavism, specifically Sri Vaishnavism)',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(120,'Dvaita Vedanta (Madhvacharya''s Commentaries)','Commentaries','',NULL,'c. 1238–1317 CE (13th-14th century).','Madhvacharya (also known as Anandatirtha or Purnaprajna), founder of the Dvaita Vedanta school, a Vaishnava tradition.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(121,'Nimbarka commentaries - Dvaitadvaita dualistic non-dualism (The primary text is the *Vedānta-pārijāta-saurabha*)','Commentaries','',NULL,'Scholarly consensus places Nimbārkācārya between the **11th and 13th century CE**. Traditional accounts, however, claim a much earlier date (e.g., 3096 BCE). The Nimbarka Sampradaya is one of the four historical Vaiṣṇava Sampradāyas.','Nimbārkācārya (Author) and Nimbarka Sampradaya (Tradition), also known as the Kumāra Sampradāya or Sanakādi Sampradāya.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(122,'Vallabhacharya Commentaries on Shuddhadvaita (e.g., Anubhāṣya, Tattvārthadīpa Nibandha, Subodhinī)','Commentaries','',NULL,'Vallabhacharya lived from 1479 to 1531 CE. His philosophical system, Shuddhadvaita, was propounded during the height of the Bhakti movement in India [1].','Vallabhacharya (1479-1531 CE), founder of the Pushti Marg (Path of Grace) sect of Vaishnavism. The tradition is also known as the Vallabha Sampradaya.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(123,'Chaitanya Mahaprabhu''s teachings - Achintya Bhedabheda Tattva','Commentaries','',NULL,'The philosophy was propagated by **Chaitanya Mahaprabhu** during his lifetime (1486–1534 CE) in Bengal and Odisha. The systematic theological framework was later developed by his six principal disciples, the **Six Goswamis of Vrindavan**, in the 16th century CE. The key text, *Chaitanya Charitamrita*, was composed in the late 16th or early 17th century CE.','The philosophy of Achintya Bhedabheda Tattva is the core teaching of the **Gaudiya Vaishnava** tradition, a school of Vedanta. Its main proponent and theological founder is **Chaitanya Mahaprabhu** (1486–1534 CE). The philosophy is systematically presented in the foundational texts of the tradition, most notably the *Chaitanya Charitamrita* by Krishnadasa Kaviraja Goswami.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(124,'Abhinavagupta''s Corpus on Kashmir Shaivism and Aesthetics (Tantrāloka and Abhinavabhāratī)','Commentaries','',NULL,'Circa 950–1016 CE. He flourished in Kashmir, which was a major center of philosophical and artistic activity during this period.','Abhinavagupta, the greatest exponent of Kashmir Shaivism (Trika system).',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(125,'Tattvacintāmaṇi (Thought-Jewel of Reality/Valid Knowledge)','Commentaries','',NULL,'The author, Gangesha Upadhyaya, flourished in the 14th century CE, with the composition of the *Tattvacintāmaṇi* generally dated to around **c. 1325 CE**. This period marks the beginning of the "Modern period" in the history of Indian logic.','Gangesha Upadhyaya (also Gangesvara Upadhyaya), the founder of the **Navya-Nyāya** (New Logic) school of Hindu philosophy. The tradition is a highly influential and technical development of the older Nyāya school.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(126,'Khaṇḍana-khaṇḍa-khādya (खण्डनखण्डखाद्यम्)','Commentaries','',NULL,'Circa **12th century CE**. Śrīharṣa is generally placed after Udayana (c. 10th-11th century CE), whose views he extensively refutes, and before Citsukha (c. 13th century CE), who was influenced by him. He is believed to have been a court poet and philosopher in the kingdom of Kanauj.','Śrīharṣa (c. 12th century CE), a prominent philosopher of the Advaita Vedānta tradition. He is considered one of the four great *khandana-kāras* (refuters) of Advaita, along with Citsukha, Madhusūdana Sarasvatī, and Nṛsiṃhāśrama.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(127,'Vijnanabhikshu''s Synthetic Philosophy (Sāṃkhya-pravacana-bhāṣya)','Commentaries','',NULL,'16th century CE (c. 1550–1600 CE). He is considered a late medieval or early modern Indian philosopher.','Vijnanabhikshu (Vijñānabhikṣu), a Vaishnavite scholar and philosopher. His work is a major contribution to the Bhedābheda Vedānta tradition, specifically a synthetic school that reconciles Sāṃkhya, Yoga, and Vedānta.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/commentaries_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(128,'Ramcharitmanas (The Holy Lake of the Acts of Rama)','Regional Literature','',NULL,'Composition began in 1574 CE (Vikram Samvat 1631) in Ayodhya, during the reign of the Mughal Emperor Akbar.','Goswami Tulsidas (c. 1511–1623 CE), a 16th-century Indian Bhakti poet in the Vaishnavite tradition, specifically the Rāmānandī Sampradāya.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/regional_literature_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(129,'Jnanesvari (also Dnyaneshwari or Bhavartha Deepika)','Regional Literature','',NULL,'Composed in **1290 CE** (13th century) in the Marathi language. Dnyaneshwar completed the work at the age of 15 or 16. This period marks a significant time in the development of regional devotional literature in India, preceding the major Bhakti movements in North India.','Sant Dnyaneshwar (also known as Jnaneshwar or Jnanadev), a 13th-century Marathi saint and poet. The text is a foundational work of the **Varkari** *sampradaya* (tradition), a devotional movement centered on the worship of the deity Vithoba (a form of Vishnu/Krishna) in Maharashtra. Philosophically, it is rooted in **Advaita Vedanta** but presents a synthesis of the three paths to liberation (Karma, Jnana, and Bhakti).',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/regional_literature_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(130,'Tirukkural (திருக்குறள்)','Regional Literature','',NULL,'The composition period is generally placed between the **1st century BCE and the 5th century CE**, corresponding to the post-Sangam period of Tamil literature. The most common scholarly consensus places it around the **2nd century CE**.','Thiruvalluvar (Tamil poet and philosopher). The text belongs to the classical Tamil literary tradition (Sangam literature) and is often referred to as the "Tamil Veda" or a universal book of ethics.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/regional_literature_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(131,'Tevaram and Tirumurai - Tamil Shaiva devotional poetry','Regional Literature','',NULL,'The hymns of the **Tevaram** were composed primarily in the **7th and 8th centuries CE**, during the Pallava period in South India. This period marks the height of the **Bhakti movement** in the Tamil region. The entire **Tirumurai** collection spans from the **6th to the 11th century CE**. The compilation of the first seven volumes (Tevaram) into the canonical collection was undertaken in the **10th century CE** by **Nambiyandar Nambi** under the patronage of the **Chola** emperor **Rajaraja I**.','The **Tevaram** (first seven volumes of the Tirumurai) was composed by the three most prominent Shaiva Tamil saints, known as the **Nayanars**: **Thirugnana Sambandar** (volumes 1-3), **Thirunavukkarasar** or **Appar** (volumes 4-6), and **Sundarar** (volume 7). The entire collection, the **Tirumurai**, is a compendium of songs by various Nayanars. The tradition is **Tamil Shaivism**, and the texts form the canonical basis for the **Shaiva Siddhanta** school of philosophy in South India and Sri Lanka.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/regional_literature_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(132,'Swami Vivekananda Complete Works - modern interpretation of Vedanta','Modern Interpretations','',NULL,'The **Complete Works** were compiled posthumously, but the material (lectures, letters, poems, and writings) was produced between the late 19th century (starting with his appearance at the 1893 Parliament of the World''s Religions) and his death in 1902. The period is considered the **modern era** of Hindu revivalism and reform.','Swami Vivekananda (1863–1902), a chief disciple of Ramakrishna Paramahamsa and founder of the Ramakrishna Math and Mission. The tradition is **Neo-Vedanta** (also called **Neo-Advaita**), a modern, universalistic reinterpretation and synthesis of classical Advaita Vedanta and Yoga.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/modern_interpretations_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(133,'Sri Aurobindo The Life Divine','Modern Interpretations','',NULL,'The work was first serialized as a series of essays in the monthly philosophical review *Arya* between **August 1914 and January 1919**. It was later revised and published in book form in two volumes: Volume I in **1939** and Volume II in **1940** (with a final revised edition in 1945). The philosophical tradition is modern, founded by Sri Aurobindo (1872–1950).','Sri Aurobindo; Integral Yoga tradition',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/modern_interpretations_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(134,'The Synthesis of Yoga','Modern Interpretations','',NULL,'Appeared serially in the monthly review ''Arya'' between August 1914 and January 1921.','Sri Aurobindo (1872–1950); Integral Yoga (Purna Yoga) tradition.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/modern_interpretations_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(135,'Sri Aurobindo: The Secret of the Veda','Modern Interpretations','',NULL,'The essays that comprise the book were originally published serially in the philosophical review *Arya* between **August 1914 and 1920**. The book was later published as a collected work.','Sri Aurobindo Ghose, a key figure in the Integral Yoga tradition. The work is a foundational text for the spiritual and philosophical movement centered at the Sri Aurobindo Ashram.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/modern_interpretations_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(136,'Swami Sivananda''s Major Works on Practical Vedanta and the Yoga of Synthesis','Modern Interpretations','',NULL,'20th Century. Swami Sivananda lived from 1887 to 1963. He founded the Divine Life Society (DLS) in 1936 and the Yoga-Vedanta Forest Academy in 1948, both in Rishikesh, India. His prolific writing and teaching career spanned the mid-20th century, making his works a significant contribution to the modern global dissemination of Yoga and Vedanta.','Swami Sivananda Saraswati (1887–1963), founder of The Divine Life Society (DLS) and the Yoga-Vedanta Forest Academy. The tradition is the **Yoga of Synthesis** (Samanvaya Yoga), rooted in Advaita Vedanta.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/modern_interpretations_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(137,'Indian Philosophy (Two Volumes) by S. Radhakrishnan','Modern Interpretations','',NULL,'**Volume I** was first published in **1923**, and **Volume II** in **1927**. The work was composed during the early 20th century, a period of intense intellectual exchange and national self-assertion in India, positioning it as a key text in the modern re-evaluation of Indian intellectual heritage.','Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan (1888–1975), a renowned Indian philosopher, statesman, and the second President of India. The work is a foundational text in modern academic Indian philosophy, written from a perspective rooted in **Advaita Vedanta** but engaging with Western philosophical standards.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_session3/modern_interpretations_comprehensive.md','Session 3 - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:13:06','2025-11-23 03:13:06');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(138,'**Viṣṇusahasranāma** (विष्णुसहस्रनाम) - The Thousand Names of Vishnu Stotra','Stotras and Devotional Hymns','',NULL,replace('The *Vishnu Sahasranama* is an integral part of the **Anushasana Parva** of the *Mahabharata* [1]. The *Mahabharata* itself is a text that evolved over centuries.\n*   **Compilation Period:** The bulk of the *Mahabharata* is generally dated between **c. 3rd Century BCE and 3rd Century CE** [2].\n*   **Textual Accretion:** The *Anushasana Parva*, along with the *Shanti Parva*, is often considered a later didactic addition or interpolation to the epic, likely composed in the **early centuries of the Common Era** (c. 1st to 4th Century CE) [2]. This period reflects the flourishing of devotional (Bhakti) literature and the consolidation of Vaishnavism.','\n',char(10)),'The text is traditionally attributed to **Vyasa** (Veda Vyasa), the legendary sage who is also credited with compiling the *Mahabharata* [1]. The *Vishnu Sahasranama* is a core text within the **Vaishnavism** tradition of Hinduism, which worships Vishnu as the Supreme God [1]. It is also highly revered in the **Smarta** tradition, particularly due to the influential commentary by **Adi Shankara** [1].',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/stotras_and_devotional_hymns_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(139,'Lalitā Sahasranāma (ललितासहस्रनाम)','Stotras and Devotional Hymns','',NULL,'The Lalita Sahasranama is found in the *Lalitopākhyāna* (section on Lalita) of the **Brahmanda Purana** [3]. While the core of the *Brahmanda Purana* is ancient, the *Lalitopākhyāna* is considered a later, sectarian addition. Scholarly estimates for the composition of the *Lalita Sahasranama* itself generally place it between the **9th and 12th centuries CE**, a period of significant development for the Shaktism and Tantra traditions in South India [10]. The earliest known manuscript dates to the 17th century CE [11].','The Lalita Sahasranama is traditionally attributed to the **eight *Vaagdevis*** (Vasini, Kameshvari, Aruna, Vimala, Jayani, Modini, Sarveshvari, and Kaulini), who are said to have composed it at the command of the Goddess Lalita herself [1]. It is a central text of **Shaktism**, the Hindu tradition focused on the worship of the Divine Feminine (*Shakti*), and is particularly important in the **Śrī Vidyā** school of Tantra [2]. The text is presented as a dialogue where the sage **Agastya** is taught the thousand names by **Hayagriva**, an incarnation of Vishnu [3].',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/stotras_and_devotional_hymns_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(140,'Śiva-mahimnaḥ Stotra (शिवमहिम्न:स्तोत्र)','Stotras and Devotional Hymns','',NULL,'The exact date of composition is unknown, but scholarly consensus places the *Śiva-mahimnaḥ Stotra* in the period of ancient devotional literature, likely **prior to the 9th century CE**. This dating is inferred from its mature style, sophisticated philosophical content, and its influence on later Sanskrit literature and commentaries, such as that by the 12th-century scholar Bopadeva.','Traditionally attributed to the **Gandharva Puṣpadanta** (celestial musician), who composed the hymn to regain his divine powers after unknowingly committing an offense against Lord Shiva. The text belongs to the devotional tradition of **Shaivism** (Śaivism).',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/stotras_and_devotional_hymns_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(141,'Hanumān Cālīsā (हनुमान चालीसा)','Stotras and Devotional Hymns','',NULL,'The *Hanumān Cālīsā* was composed by Tulsidas in the **16th century CE** [1]. Tulsidas lived from approximately 1532 to 1623 CE, placing the composition within the period of the Mughal Empire in India [7].','The text was composed by the poet-saint **Goswami Tulsidas** (गोस्वामी तुलसीदास) [1], who is also the author of the epic *Ramcharitmanas*. The tradition is rooted in the Hindu *Bhakti* (devotional) movement, specifically the *Rāmāyat* tradition, focusing on the worship of Lord Rama and his greatest devotee, Hanuman [2].',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/stotras_and_devotional_hymns_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(142,'**Soundarya Lahari** (सौन्दर्यलहरी) - "Waves of Beauty"','Stotras and Devotional Hymns','',NULL,'Attributed to **Adi Shankaracharya**, who is generally dated to the **8th century CE** (c. 788–820 CE). This places the composition within the early medieval period of Indian philosophy and the resurgence of the Advaita Vedanta school.','Adi Shankaracharya (Ādi Śaṁkarācārya). The text is a foundational work of the **Shakta** tradition, specifically the **Dakshinachara Shakta cult**, dedicated to the worship of the Divine Feminine, **Shakti** (Śaktī).',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/stotras_and_devotional_hymns_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(143,'Śrauta Sūtras (श्रौतसूत्राणि) - Vedic Ritual Texts','Vedic Rituals and Ceremonies','',NULL,replace('The Śrauta Sūtras belong to the **Sūtra period** of Vedic literature.\n*   **General Period:** Approximately **700 BCE to 300 BCE** [13].\n*   **Baudhāyana:** Considered one of the earliest, possibly dating to **800–500 BCE** [11].\n*   **Āpastamba:** Generally placed slightly later than Baudhayana, around **600 BCE** [14].\n*   **Āśvalāyana:** Also placed within the general Sūtra period, following the codification of the *Ṛgveda* tradition [4].\n\nThe texts mark the transition from the elaborate prose of the Brahmanas to the terse, aphoristic style of the Sūtras [15].','\n',char(10)),replace('The Shrauta Sutras are attributed to various Vedic sages and their schools (Shakhas). Specifically:\n*   **Baudhāyana:** Attributed to the sage Baudhayana, belonging to the **Taittirīya Shakha** of the **Krishna Yajurveda** [1] [2].\n*   **Āpastamba:** Attributed to the sage Apastamba, also belonging to the **Taittirīya Shakha** of the **Krishna Yajurveda** [3].\n*   **Āśvalāyana:** Attributed to the sage Ashvalayana, belonging to the **Shakala Shakha** of the **Rigveda** [4].','\n',char(10)),NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/vedic_rituals_and_ceremonies_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(144,'Gṛhya Sūtras (गृह्य सूत्र) - with a focus on the Āpastamba, Pāraskara, and Gobhila traditions','Vedic Rituals and Ceremonies','',NULL,'Sūtra period, generally dated between **c. 600 BCE and 300 BCE**. They mark the transition from the Brāhmaṇa and Āraṇyaka literature to the later Dharmaśāstras.',replace('The texts are attributed to the eponymous sages Āpastamba, Pāraskara, and Gobhila. They belong to the **Kalpa Sūtras**, which are part of the Vedāṅgas. Each Sūtra is affiliated with a specific Vedic school (Śākhā):\n- **Āpastamba Gṛhya Sūtra**: Kṛṣṇa Yajurveda (Taittirīya Śākhā)\n- **Pāraskara Gṛhya Sūtra**: Śukla Yajurveda (Vājasaneyi Śākhā)\n- **Gobhila Gṛhya Sūtra**: Sāma Veda (Kauthuma Śākhā)','\n',char(10)),NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/vedic_rituals_and_ceremonies_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(145,'**Yājñavalkya Smṛti** (याज्ञवल्क्य स्मृति)','Dharmasastras','',NULL,'The text is generally dated between the **3rd and 5th century CE**, placing its composition firmly within the **Gupta period** (c. 320 to 550 CE), a time often referred to as the "Golden Age" of India. Scholar Patrick Olivelle suggests a more specific dating of the **4th to 5th century CE**. This period saw a flourishing of systematic legal and philosophical literature, which is reflected in the text''s organized and systematic approach to law.','The text is named after the revered Vedic sage **Yajnavalkya** (याज्ञवल्क्य), a prominent figure in the Upanishads (like the Brihadaranyaka Upanishad). However, the Smriti itself was composed centuries after the sage''s lifetime, and is a key work within the **Dharmaśāstra** tradition. It is often associated with the Mithila region of ancient India. The most influential commentary on the text is the **Mitākṣarā** by **Vijñāneśvara** (11th-12th century CE), which became a foundational legal authority in much of India.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/dharmasastras_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(146,'Nāradasmṛti (नारदस्मृति) or Nāradīya Dharmaśāstra (नारदीय धर्मशास्त्र)','Dharmasastras','',NULL,'The text is generally dated between **100 BCE and 400 CE**. This places it in the post-Mauryan and early Gupta periods, a time of significant development in Hindu legal thought. The oldest of the three recensions, the *Nāradīyamanusaṃhitā*, is considered to be the earliest version.','Attributed to the divine sage **Nārada** (the messenger of the gods), who is portrayed as an instructor of law and politics. Scholarly consensus suggests there was no single author, but rather a compilation by an individual or group within the **Dharmaśāstra** tradition, who attributed the work to Nārada to enhance its authority.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/dharmasastras_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(147,'Parāśara Smṛti (पराशर स्मृति) or Parāśara Dharma Saṃhitā','Dharmasastras','',NULL,'The exact date is uncertain, but it is considered a later Smriti, post-dating Manusmriti and Yajnavalkya Smriti. Scholarly estimates often place the final compilation between 100 CE and 500 CE, or even later, as it is specifically designed for the Kali Yuga.','Attributed to Maharishi Parāśara (पराशर), the grandson of Vasishtha and father of Vyasa. It is a Dharmaśāstra text.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/dharmasastras_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(148,'Abhijñānaśākuntalam (अभिज्ञानशाकुन्तलम्)','Kavya and Poetic Literature','',NULL,'The play is generally dated to the **4th–5th century CE**, placing it during the classical period of Sanskrit literature, often associated with the **Gupta Empire**, considered the "Golden Age" of Indian arts and sciences.','Kālidāsa, the pre-eminent poet and playwright of classical Sanskrit literature. The work belongs to the tradition of *Nāṭaka* (classical Sanskrit drama) and *Kāvya* (poetry), distinct from the Vedic tradition.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/kavya_and_poetic_literature_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(149,'Meghadūta (मेघदूत) - The Cloud Messenger','Kavya and Poetic Literature','',NULL,'Circa 4th–5th century CE. Kālidāsa is traditionally associated with the Gupta period, often referred to as the "Golden Age" of classical Indian culture.','Kālidāsa (कालिदास), considered one of the greatest Sanskrit poets (Mahākavi). He is a central figure in classical Sanskrit literature.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/kavya_and_poetic_literature_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(150,'**Raghuvaṃśa** (रघुवंशम्) - The Dynasty of Raghu','Kavya and Poetic Literature','',NULL,'The poet **Kālidāsa** is generally placed in the **Gupta period**, with the most commonly accepted date being the **5th century CE** [1]. Though the exact date of composition is unknown, this period is considered the golden age of classical Sanskrit literature. The events described span a vast mythological and historical period, covering the entire lineage of the Solar Dynasty from Manu to Agnivarna [2].','The celebrated Sanskrit poet **Kālidāsa** [1], who is traditionally dated to the 4th–5th century CE, during the Gupta period. He is considered one of the greatest poets and dramatists in the Sanskrit language. The work belongs to the tradition of **Mahākāvya** (great epic poem) [2].',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/kavya_and_poetic_literature_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(151,'Śatakatraya (शतकत्रय) or Subhāṣita Triśati (सुभाषित त्रिशति)','Kavya and Poetic Literature','',NULL,'The author, Bhartṛhari, is generally dated to the **5th century CE** (c. 450–510 C.E.). This places the composition of the *Śatakatraya* in the classical period of Sanskrit literature, during the Gupta Empire or immediately thereafter, a time of great intellectual and artistic flourishing.','Bhartṛhari (भर्तृहरि), a celebrated Sanskrit poet and philosopher. He is also traditionally credited with the major philosophical work on language, the Vākyapadīya, though some scholars suggest there may have been two different Bhartṛharis. The tradition is rooted in classical Hindu literature and poetics (Kāvya).',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/kavya_and_poetic_literature_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(152,'Vijñāna-bhairava-tantra (विज्ञान भैरव तन्त्र)','Tantric Texts','',NULL,'The approximate period of composition is generally placed between the **7th and 8th centuries CE**. Scholar Jaideva Singh notes that it is difficult to establish an exact date, but this period is widely accepted for its emergence within the early development of Kashmir Shaivism.','The text is framed as a dialogue between **Bhairava** (a form of Shiva, representing the ultimate reality or "awesome consciousness") and the Goddess **Bhairavi** (a form of Shakti, representing the energetic and active state). It belongs to the **Kaula Trika tradition of Kashmir Shaivism**. It is also sometimes called the *Śiva-jñāna-upaniṣad* by scholars like Abhinavagupta.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/tantric_texts_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(153,'**Kulārṇava Tantra** (कुलार्णव तन्त्र)','Tantric Texts','',NULL,'The Kularnava Tantra is generally dated to the period between the **10th and 14th centuries C.E.**, with some scholars suggesting it was composed probably before the 11th century C.E. [1] [2]. A common approximate date cited is around **1150 C.E.** [3]. It is a post-Vedic text that seeks to reconcile various philosophical schools.','The Kularnava Tantra is a foundational text of the **Kaula** tradition within **Shaktism** (Śākta), which is closely related to Shaivism. The text is presented as a dialogue between Shiva (Ishvara) and his consort Parvati (Devi). The author is traditionally considered to be Shiva himself, but the compiler is unknown. It is highly esteemed by Kaula Tantriks.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/tantric_texts_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(154,'**Mahānirvāṇa Tantra** (महा निर्वाण तन्त्र) - The Tantra of the Great Liberation','Tantric Texts','',NULL,'The **Mahānirvāṇa Tantra** is considered a late Tantric text. Scholarly consensus places its composition in the **second half of the 18th century** (c. 1775–1800 CE), likely originating in Bengal. This late dating is supported by its detailed knowledge of both the Hindu Tantric tradition and the emerging Hindu-British legal system of the time, suggesting it was written to address the social and spiritual needs of the era.','The text is presented as a dialogue between **Sadāśiva** (Shiva) and his consort **Pārvatī** (Devī), the traditional format for Tantras. The actual author is anonymous. It belongs to the **Kaula** tradition within **Shaktism** and **Shaivism**. It is considered a late text of the Hindu Tantra tradition. The most influential English translation was done by the British Orientalist **Sir John Woodroffe** (writing under the pseudonym **Arthur Avalon**) in 1913.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/tantric_texts_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
INSERT INTO texts VALUES(155,'Tantrāloka (तन्त्रालोक)','Tantric Texts','',NULL,'Composed in the **10th century CE**, specifically around the late 10th to early 11th century (c. 975–1025 CE).','Abhinavagupta, a philosopher and writer of the **Kashmir Shaivism** school of Hindu philosophy. He is considered the most important exponent of the non-dual Trika system.',NULL,'completed','2025-11-22','/home/ubuntu/vedic-mastery-study/study_documents_final/tantric_texts_comprehensive.md','Final session - Completed using parallel wide research on 2025-11-22','2025-11-23 03:28:05','2025-11-23 03:28:05');
